  "prompt": "What are some cute names to call your boyfriend in Spanish?",
  "response": "Okay, here are some cute names to call your boyfriend in Spanish, categorized by their general meaning and vibe.  I've included a mix of common and slightly less common options:\n\n**Classic & Sweet:**\n\n*   **Cari\u00f1o:** (Care-een-yo) - Darling, sweetheart, love.  This is a super common and versatile option.\n*   **Amor:** (Ah-more) - Love.  Simple, direct, and always effective.\n*   **Mi amor:** (Me Ah-more) - My love. A slight variation of Amor.\n*   **Cielo:** (See-eh-loh) - Heaven, sky. Implies he's wonderful and heavenly.\n*   **Mi cielo:** (Me See-eh-loh) - My heaven, my sky.\n*   **Coraz\u00f3n:** (Core-ah-thohn) - Heart. Signifies he's close to your heart.\n*   **Mi coraz\u00f3n:** (Me core-ah-thohn) - My heart.\n*   **Querido/Querida:** (Keh-ree-doh / Keh-ree-dah) - Dear, beloved. (Use Querido for a male, Querida for a female. Make sure you use the correct gender!)\n\n**Endearing & Playful:**\n\n*   **Gordo/Gorda:** (Gohr-doh / Gohr-dah) - Fatty, chubby.  **Use with caution!**  This is affectionate in some cultures, especially among long-term couples, but it can be offensive if he's sensitive about his weight or if you don't have that kind of relationship. Only use if you KNOW he'll find it funny and sweet. (Use Gordo for a male, Gorda for a female.)\n*   **Gordito/Gordita:** (Gohr-dee-toh / Gohr-dee-tah) - Little fatty, chubby. Same warning as above, but often considered *slightly* less potentially offensive due to the diminutive \"-ito.\" (Use Gordito for a male, Gordita for a female.)\n*   **Osito:** (Oh-see-toh) - Little bear, teddy bear. Cute and cuddly.\n*   **Beb\u00e9:** (Beh-beh) - Baby.  Fairly common.\n*   **Nene/Nena:** (Neh-neh / Neh-nah) - Baby, boy/girl. Similar to Beb\u00e9, but with a slightly more playful tone. (Use Nene for a male, Nena for a female)\n*   **Mi ni\u00f1o/Mi ni\u00f1a:** (Mee neen-yo / Mee neen-yah) - My boy/My girl.\n*   **Bomb\u00f3n:** (Bom-bone) - Chocolate, sweet treat. Signifies he's a delicious treat.\n*   **Terr\u00f3n de az\u00facar:** (Teh-rone deh ah-soo-car) - Sugar cube. Very sweet.\n*   **Mu\u00f1eco/Mu\u00f1eca:** (Moon-yeh-koh / Moon-yeh-kah) - Doll. Can be cute, but can also sound a bit objectifying depending on tone. (Use Mu\u00f1eco for a male, Mu\u00f1eca for a female.)\n*   **Sol:** (Sole) - Sun.  He brightens your day.\n*   **Mi Sol:** (Mee Sole) - My Sun.\n\n**Unique & More Personal (These often come from inside jokes or qualities you admire):**\n\n*   **Rey/Reina:** (Ray / Ray-nah) - King/Queen. If you see him as your king. (Use Rey for a male, Reina for a female.)\n*   **Mi Rey/Mi Reina:** (Mee Ray / Mee Ray-nah) - My king/My queen.\n*   **Campe\u00f3n:** (Cam-peh-own) - Champion.  If he's always helping you or achieving things.\n*   **Pr\u00edncipe:** (Preen-see-peh) - Prince.  Similar to Rey but perhaps a bit more playful.\n*   **Guapo/Guapa:** (Gwah-poh / Gwah-pah) - Handsome/Beautiful.  This is more of an adjective, but can be used as a term of endearment.  \"Hola, Guapo\" (Hello, handsome). (Use Guapo for a male, Guapa for a female)\n*   **Tesoro:** (Teh-soh-roh) - Treasure.\n*   **Mi Tesoro:** (Mee Teh-soh-roh) - My Treasure.\n*   **Listillo/Listilla:** (Lis-tee-yo / Lis-tee-yah) - Smarty pants (Use Listillo for a male, Listilla for a female) This can be endearing if he's playfully clever.\n*   You can also create variations of his name or use a nickname in Spanish.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Culture:**  The appropriateness of some of these terms depends heavily on the specific Spanish-speaking culture. What's considered cute in Spain might be odd or even offensive in Mexico or Argentina.  If you're unsure, observe how other couples interact within that culture.\n*   **Personality:**  Consider your boyfriend's personality. Is he playful and relaxed, or more reserved? Choose a name that suits him.\n*   **Relationship Stage:** Some names are better suited for long-term relationships than new ones. Starting with something simple like \"Cari\u00f1o\" is always a safe bet.\n*   **Tone:**  The way you say it matters!  Even \"Gordo\" can be sweet if said with the right tone of voice.\n\n**My recommendations for starting out are:**\n\n*   **Cari\u00f1o**\n*   **Amor**\n*   **Mi amor**\n*   **Cielo**\n*   **Mi cielo**\n\nThese are generally safe and well-received across most Spanish-speaking cultures.\n\nGood luck, and have fun finding the perfect name!  \u00a1Que te diviertas! (Have fun!)\n",
